member.name: M:Microsoft.Office.Interop.Outlook._Application.AdvancedSearch(System.String,System.Object,System.Object,System.Object)
member.summary: Performs a search based on a specified DAV Searching and Locating (DASL) search string.
member.returns: A object that represents the results of the search.
member.param: The scope of the search. For example, the folder path of a folder. It is recommended that the folder path is enclosed within single quotes. Otherwise, the search might not return correct results if the folder path contains special characters including Unicode characters. To specify multiple folder paths, enclose each folder path in single quotes and separate the single quoted folder paths with a comma.
Determines if the search will include any of the folder's subfolders.
The name given as an identifier for the search.
The DASL search filter that defines the parameters of the search.

member.param: This parameter applies only to e-mail messages using Microsoft Outlook Rich Text format: it is the position where the attachment should be placed within the body text of the message. A value of 1 for the Position parameter specifies that the attachment should be positioned at the beginning of the message body. A value 'n' greater than the number of characters in the body of the e-mail item specifies that the attachment should be placed at the end. A value of 0 makes the attachment hidden.
The type of the attachment. Can be one of the constants.
The source of the attachment. This can be a file (represented by the full file system path with a file name) or an Outlook item that constitutes the attachment.

This parameter applies only if the mail item is in Rich Text format and Type is set to olByValue: the name is displayed in an Inspector object for the attachment or when viewing the properties of the attachment. If the mail item is in Plain Text or HTML format, then the attachment is displayed using the file name in the Source parameter.

Use this class only when you have to access an earlier event in this class that has been subsequently extended in a later version of Outlook.
